Scaffold every path with beats. A beat is one concrete story moment (a 1-3
sentence summary of what happens). Each dilemma gets a Y-shaped scaffold:
a shared pre-commit chain experienced by every player, then a fork into the two
paths, each with its commit beat (the point of no return, where the choice locks in)
and post-commit beats (playing out that answer's consequences).

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}, {{ vision.tone }}. Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}.
POINT OF VIEW (the story's intended viewpoint): {{ vision.effective_pov_hint or "one limited viewpoint" }}.
Most beats should be something a character present in the scene lives through — let an
ordinary outcome reach the story through someone on the page, not as an omniscient
report. But an ending may close on a brief CODA that steps outside any single
character — a fate, or what becomes of a person, place, or object once the story is
over — when the drama earns one; keep such a coda short (a later stage frames it).
Don't inflate an ordinary perceivable outcome into an omniscient scene, and don't
force a genuine epilogue into one character's eyes either.

RETAINED CAST:
{% for e in entities %}
- {{ e.id }} — {{ e.name }}: {{ e.concept }}
{% endfor %}

DILEMMAS AND PATHS:
{% for d in dilemmas %}
- {{ d.dilemma.id }} ({{ d.dilemma.role }}{% if d.locked %}, LOCKED — single path, scaffold under locked_scaffolds{% endif %}): {{ d.dilemma.question }}
{% for p in d.paths %}
  - {{ p.id }}: answer "{{ p.answer }}" — consequences: {{ p.consequences | join("; ") }}
{% endfor %}
{% endfor %}

{% set shape = scope.shape %}
REQUIREMENTS:
- setup: {{ shape.setup[0] }}-{{ shape.setup[1] }} structural beats of world-building that open the story before any
  dilemma is introduced.
- Every beat except setup and commit beats carries an effect: "advances"
  (the default — the storyline moves), "reveals" (a truth surfaces), or
  "complicates" (doubt deepens). A commit beat's effect is implied — the
  commitment itself.
- scaffolds: one entry per BRANCHED dilemma (two paths), naming its two paths
  exactly as listed above.
- locked_scaffolds: one entry per LOCKED dilemma. A locked storyline is a
  fork-less subplot every player experiences: lead_in ({{ shape.locked_lead_in[0] }}-{{ shape.locked_lead_in[1] }} beats that introduce
  and develop the question), resolution (ONE beat where the
  story settles it — the explored answer becomes fact, no player choice), and
  aftermath ({{ shape.locked_aftermath[0] }}-{{ shape.locked_aftermath[1] }} beats playing out what the resolution leaves behind). It must
  read as a complete mini-story on its own, and it must never end the story:
  no is_ending anywhere in a locked chain. Entry: {"dilemma", "path",
  "lead_in": [...], "resolution": {...}, "aftermath": [...]} with ordinary
  beat objects.
- pre_commit: {{ shape.pre_commit[0] }}-{{ shape.pre_commit[1] }} beats per dilemma that introduce and develop the question —
  every player sees these regardless of their eventual choice.
  A deep chain must ESCALATE, never idle: each beat raises the cost of both
  answers or narrows the room to avoid choosing — cut any beat that only
  restates the stakes.
- Each path: one commit beat (the irreversible act itself — concrete and dramatic)
  and {{ shape.post_commit[0] }}-{{ shape.post_commit[1] }} post_commit beats proving that answer — consequences compounding,
  not aftermath padding.
- HARD dilemma paths never rejoin: their final post-commit beat is an ending
  (is_ending: true) that resolves the whole story for that world. With more than
  one hard dilemma, a later stage nests their forks (the story forks once, then
  forks again inside each world, and endings multiply); still author every hard
  Y complete with endings as above — the engine keeps only the climax fork's.
- SOFT dilemma paths will reconverge later (a later stage wires it): give each
  soft path at least {{ scope.min_payoff_beats }} post-commit payoff beat(s); do NOT mark soft beats as endings.
- Each beat's story must read coherently along its own path: if you read one
  path's beats in order they form a complete mini-story.
- Where a beat's timing relative to ANOTHER dilemma matters, add a temporal hint:
  hints: [{"dilemma": "dilemma:other", "position": "before_commit" | "after_commit"}]
  — "this beat should land before/after that dilemma's point of no return". A later
  stage interleaves the scaffolds and uses these to order scenes. Hints are optional
  and advisory; use them only where the drama genuinely demands an ordering. Only
  the movable beats are read for hints — pre-commit beats and locked-storyline
  beats; a hint on a commit or post-commit beat is ignored (those travel with
  their dilemma's resolution as one block).
- Where a beat's scene could flex to co-occur with another dilemma's business (same
  place, same people), note it in one sentence: flexibility: "the soundings could be
  read anywhere Elias works". These invite the interleaver to merge scenes. Optional,
  and meaningful only on pre-commit and locked-storyline beats — the beats every
  player sees are the only ones that can share a scene.
- Beat ids: beat:slug. Reference entity ids in each beat's entities list.
